\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Chapter 3: The War of the Pacific (1879\'961883)
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Summary of the Critical Juncture (CJ):
\f1\b0  Triggered by disputes over saltpeter, this CJ exposed the complete absence of a functional, unified national state. It resulted in military defeat, territorial loss, the destruction of the economy, and a chaotic reconstruction period led by military caudillos and emerging civilian elites.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Bottom-up Democratic Process?
\f1\b0  This CJ was not initiated by a bottom-up process, but it sparked one during the wartime resistance. Indigenous peasants and 
\f2\i montoneras
\f1\i0  (guerrillas) mobilized to fight alongside military leaders like Andr\'e9s A. C\'e1ceres, using their participation to demand the elimination of the oppressive indigenous tribute and to fight for political inclusion. However, once in power, C\'e1ceres allied with the landowning elite and turned his back on the peasants, thwarting this bottom-up democratizing effort.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Portfolios and Sectors Involved:
\f1\b0  The core demands centered heavily on the 
\f0\b Economy (Hacienda)
\f1\b0  and 
\f0\b War/Interior
\f1\b0  sectors. The peasant uprisings were driven by economic demands to eliminate the indigenous tribute, while the state's budget was almost entirely consumed by the military and foreign debt. During the reconstruction, civilian elites pushed for fiscal decentralization so that local departments could manage their own 
\f0\b Public Goods
\f1\b0 , such as education, roads, and bridges.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 \strokec2 Chapter 4: The Crisis of the Aristocratic Republic (1920\'961933)
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Summary of the CJ:
\f1\b0  The collapse of the exclusionary oligarchic state was triggered by the 1929 global economic depression, the fall of the Legu\'eda dictatorship, and extreme political polarization. This era saw the emergence of mass political parties (APRA and the Communist Party) and culminated in the bloody Trujillo insurrection of 1932, the assassination of President S\'e1nchez Cerro, and the restrictive 1933 Constitution.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Bottom-up Democratic Process?
\f1\b0  
\f0\b Yes.
\f1\b0  This CJ was heavily driven by massive bottom-up social mobilizations. It featured indigenous uprisings in the southern Andes (like the Rumi Maqui rebellion), an aggressive urban labor movement fighting for the 8-hour workday, and university students demanding academic reform. These groups actively fought against a "competitive oligarchy" that restricted voting to only 2% of the population.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Portfolios and Sectors Involved:
\f1\b0  The demands were a broad mix of 
\f0\b Labor, Public Goods, and Political Rights
\f1\b0 . The working classes demanded fair wages and labor protections. APRA's "Minimum Plan" heavily targeted the 
\f0\b Economy sector
\f1\b0  by demanding taxes on large landowners, while simultaneously demanding vast 
\f0\b Public Goods
\f1\b0  (universal free education, social security) and full 
\f0\b Political Rights
\f1\b0  (universal suffrage for everyone over 18, including women).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 \strokec2 Chapter 5: The Military Revolution (1968\'961975)
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Summary of the CJ:
\f1\b0  Triggered by a coup led by radical military officers (General Velasco Alvarado), this CJ permanently dismantled the traditional oligarchy and the semi-feudal 
\f2\i gamonalismo
\f1\i0  system through a radical agrarian reform and the nationalization of foreign enclaves.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Bottom-up Democratic Process?
\f1\b0  The CJ was initiated as a top-down military intervention specifically designed to preempt and control a massive bottom-up democratic overflow. During the 1950s and 1960s, a vigorous bottom-up process of rural unionization, massive peasant land invasions (e.g., in La Convenci\'f3n), and urban migrations overwhelmed the oligarchic state. To prevent a radical communist revolution from below, the military stepped in to execute structural reforms from above, resulting in "democratization without democracy" via corporatist state organizations like SINAMOS.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Portfolios and Sectors Involved:
\f1\b0  The focus shifted heavily toward 
\f0\b Agriculture, Public Goods, and the Economy
\f1\b0 , while 
\f0\b Political Rights
\f1\b0  (like voting and free speech) were explicitly suppressed by the dictatorship. The peasants' primary demand was land ownership, placing the 
\f0\b Ministry of Agriculture
\f1\b0  at the center of executing the Agrarian Reform. Urban migrants demanded public goods like housing, water, and schools. To manage the new state-capitalist model, the military drastically expanded the state's economic portfolios, creating the Ministries of Industry, Fishery, and Energy and Mines.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 \strokec2 Chapter 6: Terrorism, Hyperinflation, and Fujimori's Coup (1980\'961992)
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Summary of the CJ:
\f1\b0  Defined by the brutal armed conflict against Sendero Luminoso and MRTA, the economic devastation of the 1980s (where heterodox policies led to 7,500% hyperinflation), and the total collapse of the traditional political party system. It ended with Fujimori's 1992 
\f2\i autogolpe
\f1\i0  and the imposition of a neoliberal constitution in 1993.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Bottom-up Democratic Process?
\f1\b0  
\f0\b No.
\f1\b0  This period represents a severe process of 
\f0\b de-democratization
\f1\b0 . Although the 1980s began with the granting of universal suffrage to illiterates, the extreme violence of Sendero Luminoso and the subsequent state terrorism systematically assassinated grassroots leaders, destroyed social organizations, and paralyzed civil society. Sendero Luminoso explicitly rejected bottom-up democratic negotiations, boycotting elections and using terror to create power vacuums.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Portfolios and Sectors Involved:
\f1\b0  The sheer scale of the crisis forced the state to prioritize survival, placing the 
\f0\b Ministry of Economy and Finance (MEF)
\f1\b0  and the 
\f0\b Ministries of Defense and Interior (PCM)
\f1\b0  at the absolute center of governance. The hyperinflation crisis demanded radical economic stabilization and structural adjustments, making the Economy sector the focal point for international creditors (IMF) and domestic survival. Concurrently, the terrorist threat led to the creation of Political-Military Commands, transferring massive state power and territorial control to the Defense sector. Demands for public goods and social rights collapsed as the state went bankrupt, reducing social spending to historical lows.\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
